The epitope possesses a non-standard PΩ anchor residue AlaP10 forming a set of conserved hydrogen bonds with MHC side chains. The peptide rises above the floor of the binding site and kinks between AlaP6 and SerP8. Consequently, AlaP7 is completely solvent-exposed. Only hydrogen bonds crucial for the conformation of C-terminal part of the peptide are discussed in the paper and curated. They result in an overall shift of the peptide backbone towards the alpha2-helix of MHC, when compared to other H-2D(b)-bound peptides.

The epitope is an analog of peptide MBP(1-11). To cater for the requirement of an in vivo posttranslational acetylation of the MBP N-terminus, a Glycine residue was added at the beginning of the peptide, at position MBP-0. This residue mimics the acetyl needed group. Also, to enhance the binding affinity of the epitope to the MHC, a mutation was introduced: K4 -> Y4. Next, three additional residues from the leader sequence S-3, R-2, G-1 remained at the N-terminus as part of the epitope. Finally, at the peptide C-terminus, the first eight residues from the peptide linker remain as part of the peptide sequence.
